<!DOCTYPE html>
<!--
  Thoth single-image template: funnel-card
  Best for: a funnel / pyramid post — a sequence of named tiers whose WIDTH steps
            down (or up) so the stack reads as a funnel or a pyramid silhouette.
            (cf. catalog "Funnel/Pyramid", "Craft Your POV" funnel,
            "5 Layers Behind OKR Execution" pyramid.)

  Content fields (from render.js):
    eyebrow        optional   small uppercase caption above the headline
    headline       required   the title (e.g. "The retention funnel")
    pill           optional   one word/phrase punched into the lockup's display pill
    subhead        optional   one muted line under the lockup
    orientation    optional   "funnel" (default) = widest tier at TOP, narrowing
                              down. "pyramid" = widest at BOTTOM, narrowing up.
                              HUMAN-READABLE only; the template branches on the
                              derived boolean is_pyramid (see below).
    is_pyramid     optional   truthy ONLY when orientation == "pyramid". Adds the
                              .pyramid modifier that flips the width ramp. (The
                              mustache engine can't compare strings, so a funnel
                              vs pyramid switch needs this explicit boolean, the
                              same pattern bar-chart-card uses for barN_accent.)
    tier1_label    required   TOP tier label (band 1, at the top of the stack)
    tier1_desc     optional   one short line under tier 1's label
    tier2_label..tier5_label  optional   additional tier labels, top -> down
    tier2_desc..tier5_desc    optional   matching one-line descriptions
    type_label     optional   footer genre label (e.g. "Framework")
    attribution    optional   default: {{handle}}

  Renders 3–5 tiers. Each tier is a FIXED numbered slot wrapped in a single
  {{#tierN_label}}...{{/tierN_label}} conditional, so unused slots vanish and one
  .tier selector animates them all in DOM order (top -> bottom). The mustache
  engine now nests, but tierN_desc stays a bare {{tierN_desc}} that collapses via
  the .tier-desc:empty rule when absent — no inner conditional needed.

  Re-skin: every band is a kit "sticker" .card — a palette SWATCH fill
  (.fill-1..5), the kit outline (var(--card-stroke) / -w), kit corner radius
  (var(--card-radius)) and the kit drop-shadow. A square .badge numbers each
  tier top->down (1 = top); a bold centered label + optional muted desc sit
  inside. Width steps per tier to draw the silhouette. Matches steps-card /
  layers-card lockup, persona font, gradient bg, footer, and density — all
  token-driven so a persona's brand.yaml restyles the whole family at once.
-->
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <style>{{tokens_css}}{{base_css}}
    .funnel-headline { max-width: 880px; margin-top: var(--space-3); margin-bottom: var(--space-2); }
    .funnel-headline .pill { font-size: 0.92em; }
    .subtitle { margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }

    /* The tier stack: centered column of width-stepped sticker bands. Centered
       so each band's silhouette steps symmetrically around the spine. */
    .funnel-stack {
      flex: 1;
      min-height: 0;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      gap: var(--space-3);
    }

    /* One tier band. Inherits the kit sticker look from .card; the per-tier
       .fill-N class supplies a palette swatch. Content is CENTERED so labels
       stay legible even in the narrowest bands. Padding is tightened from the
       kit default so five bands + gaps fit the usable height. */
    .tier {
      width: 100%;                       /* per-tier width set by .t1..t5 below */
      padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);   /* tightened from kit default so 5 bands + gaps fit usable height */
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      text-align: center;
      overflow: hidden;
    }

    /* Badge + label ride on one centered line so even narrow bands read as a
       single labeled chip; the desc tucks under it. */
    .tier-head {
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      gap: var(--space-2);
      min-width: 0;
      max-width: 100%;
    }
    /* Smaller than the kit default so it fits the shorter bands; still the
       ink/bg sticker glyph used across the family. */
    .tier .badge {
      width: 48px; height: 48px;
      border-radius: 14px;
      font-size: 26px;
    }
    .tier-label {
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-weight: var(--weight-headline);
      font-size: 38px;
      line-height: 1.0;
      letter-spacing: -0.02em;
      color: var(--brand-ink);
      white-space: nowrap;
      overflow: hidden;
      text-overflow: ellipsis;
      min-width: 0;
    }
    .tier-desc {
      font-family: var(--font-body);
      font-size: var(--size-caption);
      font-weight: var(--weight-body);
      line-height: var(--leading-normal);
      color: var(--brand-muted);
      margin-top: 6px;
      white-space: nowrap;
      overflow: hidden;
      text-overflow: ellipsis;
      max-width: 100%;
    }
    /* Bare {{tierN_desc}} renders empty when absent -> collapse the line. */
    .tier-desc:empty { display: none; }

    /* FUNNEL width ramp (default): tier1 (top) widest, narrowing downward.
       Resting state = final visible look; rowReveal/layerReveal only animate
       transforms, so the static PNG is correct with no JS. */
    .t1 { width: 100%; }
    .t2 { width: 82%; }
    .t3 { width: 64%; }
    .t4 { width: 46%; }
    .t5 { width: 32%; }

    /* PYRAMID modifier: flip the ramp so the WIDEST band is at the BOTTOM.
       Width is keyed off how many tiers render (the deepest filled tier must be
       the 100%-wide base), so .pyramid reverses per render-arity. The active set
       is selected by the body's tier-count class (.has-3 / .has-4 / .has-5),
       set from the is_pyramid + hasN flags below. */
    .pyramid.has-5 .t1 { width: 32%; }
    .pyramid.has-5 .t2 { width: 46%; }
    .pyramid.has-5 .t3 { width: 64%; }
    .pyramid.has-5 .t4 { width: 82%; }
    .pyramid.has-5 .t5 { width: 100%; }

    .pyramid.has-4 .t1 { width: 40%; }
    .pyramid.has-4 .t2 { width: 60%; }
    .pyramid.has-4 .t3 { width: 80%; }
    .pyramid.has-4 .t4 { width: 100%; }

    .pyramid.has-3 .t1 { width: 50%; }
    .pyramid.has-3 .t2 { width: 76%; }
    .pyramid.has-3 .t3 { width: 100%; }
  </style>
</head>
<body class="{{#is_pyramid}}pyramid {{/is_pyramid}}{{#has5}}has-5{{/has5}}{{#has4}}has-4{{/has4}}{{#has3}}has-3{{/has3}}">
  <div class="canvas">
    <header class="canvas-header">
      {{#eyebrow}}<span class="text-caption">{{eyebrow}}</span>{{/eyebrow}}
      <span class="accent-dot"></span>
    </header>

    <h1 class="text-headline-sm funnel-headline lockup">
      <span>{{headline}}</span>{{#pill}} <span class="pill">{{pill}}</span>{{/pill}}
    </h1>
    {{#subhead}}<p class="subtitle">{{subhead}}</p>{{/subhead}}

    <!-- Tier bands in DOM order TOP -> BOTTOM. tier1 = top, highest-numbered =
         bottom. The per-tier .tN class sets the width (funnel default; .pyramid
         flips it). The badge number is fixed per slot so it reads top->down. -->
    <div class="funnel-stack">
      {{#tier1_label}}<div class="tier t1 card fill-1">
        <div class="tier-head">
          <span class="badge">1</span>
          <span class="tier-label">{{tier1_label}}</span>
        </div>
        <span class="tier-desc">{{tier1_desc}}</span>
      </div>{{/tier1_label}}
      {{#tier2_label}}<div class="tier t2 card fill-2">
        <div class="tier-head">
          <span class="badge">2</span>
          <span class="tier-label">{{tier2_label}}</span>
        </div>
        <span class="tier-desc">{{tier2_desc}}</span>
      </div>{{/tier2_label}}
      {{#tier3_label}}<div class="tier t3 card fill-3">
        <div class="tier-head">
          <span class="badge">3</span>
          <span class="tier-label">{{tier3_label}}</span>
        </div>
        <span class="tier-desc">{{tier3_desc}}</span>
      </div>{{/tier3_label}}
      {{#tier4_label}}<div class="tier t4 card fill-4">
        <div class="tier-head">
          <span class="badge">4</span>
          <span class="tier-label">{{tier4_label}}</span>
        </div>
        <span class="tier-desc">{{tier4_desc}}</span>
      </div>{{/tier4_label}}
      {{#tier5_label}}<div class="tier t5 card fill-5">
        <div class="tier-head">
          <span class="badge">5</span>
          <span class="tier-label">{{tier5_label}}</span>
        </div>
        <span class="tier-desc">{{tier5_desc}}</span>
      </div>{{/tier5_label}}
    </div>

    <footer class="canvas-footer">
      <span class="handle">{{attribution}}</span>
      <span>{{type_label}}</span>
    </footer>
  </div>

  <script>
    /* Animation spec — composes shared primitives from window.__thothMotion,
       which render.js injects in GIF mode. Static PNG mode never calls build(),
       so the card renders in its final resting state from CSS.

       The tiers pop in IN ORDER along the funnel's flow via a single layerReveal
       (one reveal primitive per element group, like layers-card / steps-card —
       no overlapping opacity tweens). .tier elements are in DOM order top ->
       bottom: for a funnel that IS the flow (top -> down), so a forward stagger
       is correct. For a pyramid the build should pop bottom -> up; render.js
       can't read the template's orientation, so the template reverses the
       element list itself when the .pyramid modifier is present (see below). */
    window.__thothAnim = {
      duration: 5.2,
      build: function (gsap) {
        var M = window.__thothMotion, tl = gsap.timeline({ paused: true });
        M.fadeUp(gsap, tl, '.canvas-header', 0.15, { y: -24, duration: 0.5 });
        M.fadeUp(gsap, tl, '.funnel-headline', 0.45, { y: 28, duration: 0.55 });
        M.layerReveal(gsap, tl, '.pill', 0.95, { scaleFrom: 0.5, duration: 0.4 });
        M.fadeUp(gsap, tl, '.subtitle', 1.15, { y: 16, duration: 0.5 });

        // Tier reveal — pop each band in along the funnel's flow. For a funnel
        // that's top -> down (DOM order); for a pyramid, bottom -> up, so feed
        // layerReveal the band list reversed. We pass an explicit element array
        // (layerReveal accepts a NodeList/array) so the stagger direction tracks
        // orientation without any inline animation math.
        var tiers = Array.prototype.slice.call(document.querySelectorAll('.tier'));
        if (document.body.classList.contains('pyramid')) tiers.reverse();
        M.layerReveal(gsap, tl, tiers, 1.6, {
          scaleFrom: 0.6, origin: '50% 50%', duration: 0.55, stagger: 0.55
        });

        M.fadeUp(gsap, tl, '.canvas-footer', 4.7, { duration: 0.5 });
        return tl;
      }
    };
  </script>
</body>
</html>
